This version is designed so it could plausibly be read by older teenagers or first-year undergraduates, or adapted into a short book.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The subject is Ludwig Wittgenstein (reference only; not repeated inside LaTeX).</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Chaptered LaTeX Biography with Parables</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\section*{Ludwig Wittgenstein: Learning When Not to Speak}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Chapter 1: A House Full of Music and Rules}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Ludwig Wittgenstein was born in Vienna in 1889, into a family of remarkable wealth and discipline. His home was filled with music, visiting artists, and exacting expectations. Playing an instrument was not a hobby but a responsibility. Conversation was sharp, often demanding, and rarely sentimental.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">From childhood, Wittgenstein learned an unusual lesson: that beauty does not need explanation, and that seriousness does not need display. Music was not discussed so much as respected. Feelings were not paraded; they were endured.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This early environment taught him something that would later become philosophical: that what matters most often resists being put into words.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Chapter 2: Machines, Diagrams, and Exactness}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">As a young man, Wittgenstein studied engineering. He liked problems where mistakes had consequences. A machine either works or it does not. Precision is not optional.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">While studying machines, however, he became fascinated by diagrams. A drawing on paper could represent something real and complex. But how? What gives a diagram its power to mean something?</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This question pulled him away from engineering and toward logic. He began to suspect that language itself works like a diagram: not by resembling the world visually, but by sharing its structure.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Chapter 3: The World as a Picture}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein came to believe that meaningful sentences function like pictures. This did not mean that words look like things, but that they are arranged in ways that mirror how things could be.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A sentence such as ŌĆ£The cup is on the tableŌĆØ works because its parts stand in a relation that could exist in the world. If the relation exists, the sentence is true. If not, it is false.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">But some sentences fail in a different way. They do not match reality, not because reality disagrees, but because there is nothing they could possibly match. These sentences do not describe facts at all.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein believed many philosophical confusions arise from treating such sentences as if they were saying something, when they are not.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Parable: The Map That Promised Too Much}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Imagine a map that claims to show not only streets and rivers, but also happiness, goodness, and the meaning of life. You look closely, but there are no symbols for these things.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The problem is not that the map is incomplete. The problem is that maps are not meant to show those things at all.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein believed language is like that map. When we ask it to do what it cannot, confusion follows.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Chapter 4: War and the Weight of Words}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">When the First World War began, Wittgenstein volunteered for service. He lived close to danger and uncertainty. In war, words lose their decoration. Commands, warnings, and facts matter. Speeches do not.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">During this time, he wrote notes that mixed logic with reflections on fear, courage, and responsibility. He came to believe that ethics is not a subject one can lecture about without risk.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">To speak about goodness as if it were a fact among facts can turn morality into performance. Some kinds of speech do not merely describe; they authorize. They allow people to feel moral without being moral.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">From this period came one of his most famous conclusions: that some things must be shown by how one lives, not said.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Chapter 5: The Ladder and the Silence}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">In his early philosophy, Wittgenstein compared his own explanations to a ladder. The ladder helps you climb to a clearer viewŌĆöbut once there, you must let it go.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Philosophy, he believed, should not provide grand theories about life. It should remove confusion. Once the confusion is gone, the explanations themselves are no longer needed.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This is why he ended his early work by saying that what cannot be spoken of must be passed over in silence. Silence was not ignorance. It was restraint.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Chapter 6: Giving Away What Weighs You Down}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">After the war, Wittgenstein gave away his fortune. He believed wealth interfered with honesty by cushioning failure and dulling responsibility. He chose instead to live simply.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He worked as a village schoolteacher and later in manual labor. He was demanding and often unhappy, especially when he felt he had failed to live up to his own standards.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">What he could not tolerate was hypocrisy: saying one thing and living another. For him, ethics was first a duty to oneselfŌĆöto live without excuses.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Chapter 7: Language in Use}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Years later, Wittgenstein began to doubt his earlier ideas. He no longer believed language had a single hidden structure. Instead, he noticed that words do many different things.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Some words describe, some command, some comfort, some joke. Their meaning lies in how they are used, not in an invisible logical form.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He called these different uses \emph{language games}. To understand a word is to understand how it functions in life.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Parable: The Toolbox}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Imagine opening a toolbox. Inside are hammers, rulers, saws, and screws. It would be strange to ask what all these tools have in common beyond being tools.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Words are like that. Trying to force them all into one model causes confusion.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Chapter 8: Family Resemblance}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein noticed that many concepts lack a single defining feature. Consider the word ŌĆ£game.ŌĆØ Board games, sports, and childrenŌĆÖs games do not all share one trait. Yet we recognize them as related.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He called this pattern \emph{family resemblance}. Concepts are connected by overlapping similarities, not by essence.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Any serious causal theory of meaning, he believed, must respect this complexity instead of simplifying it away.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Chapter 9: Different Lives, Different Languages}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein lived in a time when men and women often inhabited separate social worlds. He understood that language grows out of these worlds.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Many misunderstandings occur when words developed in one form of life are applied blindly to another. Philosophy often fails, he thought, because it ignores this.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Understanding requires attention, humility, and observation.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Chapter 10: Music, Beauty, and Conduct}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Music remained sacred to Wittgenstein throughout his life. A musical phrase could express what no explanation could.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He believed philosophy should aspire to the condition of music: exact, restrained, and irreducible.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Ethics, too, was not a theory but a way of standing in the world. To behave well was not to follow rules, but to live without self-deception.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Chapter 11: Leaving the Lecture Hall}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Though he taught at Cambridge and influenced generations, Wittgenstein was uneasy with academic philosophy. He distrusted cleverness detached from life.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He wrote little, revised endlessly, and doubted whether writing was justified at all. Philosophy, he believed, should make itself unnecessary.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Epilogue: Learning When to Stop}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">WittgensteinŌĆÖs life suggests an unusual lesson: that clarity is not achieved by saying more, but by knowing when to stop.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Some things are not protected by explanation, but by care. Some truths survive only when they are lived rather than spoken.</p>
