="12" r="1"></circle><circle cx="19" cy="12" r="1"></circle><circle cx="5" cy="12" r="1"></circle></svg></span></button></div></div><div style="height: 1px; position: absolute; bottom: 0px; z-index: 1000;"></div></div><div class="w-full flex-col mx-auto flex max-w-[--content-max-width]" id="last-reply-container" style="--gutter-width: calc((100cqw - var(--content-width)) / 2);"><div class="flex flex-col items-center"><div class="relative group flex flex-col justify-center w-full max-w-[var(--content-max-width)] pb-0.5 items-end" id="response-abe821b9-4f96-44ec-b6a9-dfc6adcda9e4" style="scroll-margin-top: var(--scroll-margin-top, 0px);"><div dir="auto" class="message-bubble relative rounded-3xl text-primary min-h-7 prose dark:prose-invert break-words prose-p:opacity-100 prose-strong:opacity-100 prose-li:opacity-100 prose-ul:opacity-100 prose-ol:opacity-100 prose-ul:my-1 prose-ol:my-1 prose-li:my-2 last:prose-li:mb-3 prose-li:ps-1 prose-li:ms-1 bg-surface-l1 border border-border-l1 max-w-[100%] @sm/mainview:max-w-[90%] px-4 rounded-br-lg"><div class="relative"><div class="relative"><div class="relative response-content-markdown markdown [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:text-current [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose):hover]:text-primary [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose):hover]:decoration-primary [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:underline [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:decoration-primary/30 [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:underline-offset-2 [&amp;_h2:not(.not-prose):first-child]:mt-0 [&amp;_h3:not(.not-prose):first-child]:mt-0 [&amp;_h4:not(.not-prose):first-child]:mt-0"><p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Help me get an outline for the book we might have to move some sections around and add some: \section*{Ludwig Wittgenstein: A Life Oriented Toward Clarity}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Ludwig Wittgenstein was born in Vienna in 1889 into a family of immense wealth and cultural seriousness. His childhood unfolded in an environment where music, engineering, and intellectual discipline were treated not as luxuries but as obligations. The household was filled with accomplished musicians and technically gifted thinkers. Standards were high, and emotional expression was restrained. One was expected to endure intensity rather than display it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">From an early age, Wittgenstein absorbed the idea that inner life carries weight. Feelings were not denied, but they were not explained away or dramatized. Beauty was present, but it was not discussed as an opinion. Music, especially, was treated as something one answered to rather than consumed.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This atmosphere left a lasting mark. Wittgenstein grew up believing that carelessness was not merely a practical failure but a moral one. Precision was a form of respect. To do something poorly was to fail to take it seriously enough.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Engineering and the Discipline of Exactness}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein did not initially set out to become a philosopher. He studied engineering, attracted by problems that demanded rigor and left no room for ambiguity. A machine either functions or it does not. A design either holds or fails. In engineering, explanations must eventually submit to reality.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Yet even as he worked on technical problems, Wittgenstein became uneasy. He noticed that diagrams, formulas, and schematics were doing something remarkable: they represented complex realities through structure alone. A drawing could stand in for a mechanism. A formula could capture a process. Representation itself became a problem.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">What makes a diagram meaningful? Why does one arrangement of marks say something about the world while another does not?</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">These questions pulled him away from engineering and toward logic. Logic, for Wittgenstein, was not a game of symbols. It was an investigation into the conditions that make representation possible at all.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Search for Logical Form}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein became convinced that language works because it shares a structure with the world. Words do not merely label things; they stand in relations that mirror how things can stand in reality. To understand language, one must understand this shared structure.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This idea culminated in his early philosophical work, which would later be published as the \emph{Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus}. The book is short, austere, and written in numbered propositions. It reads less like a treatise and more like a set of precise steps laid out for careful inspection.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The central claim of the \emph{Tractatus} is that the world consists of facts, not things. A fact is not an object, but a configuration: things standing in relation. Language mirrors this. A meaningful sentence does not name an object; it depicts a possible arrangement of objects.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Picture Theory of Language}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">According to what later came to be called the \emph{picture theory of language}, a sentence functions like a picture. This does not mean that sentences resemble reality visually. Rather, they resemble reality logically.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Just as a map represents a city by arranging symbols in relations that correspond to streets and intersections, a sentence represents a possible situation by arranging words in relations that correspond to how things might stand in the world.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">If the arrangement matches reality, the sentence is true.
If it does not, the sentence is false.
But if there is no possible reality that could match the arrangement, then the sentence does not describe anything at all.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This distinction was crucial for Wittgenstein. Many philosophical problems, he believed, arise because people fail to notice when language has slipped beyond its capacity to represent.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Parable: The Faultless Map}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Imagine a map drawn with perfect precision. Every street, river, and building is correctly placed. Now imagine someone asking where kindness is located on the map, or how much meaning lies between two intersections.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The map has not failed. The question has.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein believed that language often suffers the same misuse. We ask it to show what it was never designed to show, and then blame it for our confusion.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Sense, Nonsense, and the Limits of Philosophy}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">For Wittgenstein, a sentence that fails to picture a possible fact is not false in the ordinary sense. It is nonsensical. This does not mean it is foolish or trivial. It means that it does not succeed in saying anything.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Much traditional philosophy, he believed, consisted of such sentences. Metaphysical claims often look like statements but fail to depict any possible situation. They gesture beyond the limits of sense.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Philosophy, therefore, should not compete with science by offering theories about the world. Its task is diagnostic. It clarifies what can be said and exposes what only appears to be said.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">In this early view, philosophy is not a body of knowledge but an activity: the careful untangling of language.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\section*{Logic, Foundations, and the Question of Certainty}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">At the beginning of the twentieth century, mathematics itself appeared to be uncertain in a new and troubling way. Mathematicians had achieved extraordinary results, yet disagreement lingered about the very nature of numbers, proof, and logical necessity. The more rigorously these questions were pursued, the less obvious the answers became.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">One of the most influential attempts to resolve this uncertainty came from the philosopher and mathematician Bertrand Russell. In 1903, Russell published \emph{The Principles of Mathematics}, a bold work that argued that mathematics could be reduced to logic. According to this view, numbers were not mysterious entities but logical constructionsŌĆöclasses, or what later came to be called sets.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The ambition of the project was enormous. If mathematics could be shown to rest entirely on logic, then its certainty would no longer depend on intuition or convention. Mathematics would become an extension of pure reasoning.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Yet almost as soon as Russell completed the work, a problem emerged at its core.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{RussellŌĆÖs Paradox}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The difficulty, now known as RussellŌĆÖs Paradox, revealed a contradiction in the theory of classes. Some collections could not consistently be treated as members of themselves or as non-members of themselves without contradiction. The paradox was not peripheral. It struck at the foundation of the entire project.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Here was a theory that aimed at absolute clarity and instead produced inconsistency.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">For many thinkers, this was a technical problem to be repaired. For Wittgenstein, it was something else entirely. He became gripped by the conviction that the contradiction was not accidental. It revealed a deeper misunderstanding of what logic itself is.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Russell had asked: What is mathematics?
Wittgenstein began to ask: What is logic?</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Arrival at Cambridge}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">In 1911, Wittgenstein went to Cambridge. He did not apply in the ordinary way. He arrived without credentials, without having studied philosophy formally, and without having read most of the philosophical canon. He had read Russell. He had read Gottlob Frege. That was nearly all.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Rather than enrolling as a student, he sought out Russell directly.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Russell was initially uncertain how to understand him. Wittgenstein did not behave like a conventional student. He was intense, uncompromising, and uninterested in academic rituals. Russell later recalled that he was unsure whether Wittgenstein was mad or a genius.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Within less than a year, RussellŌĆÖs judgment had changed completely.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">In the summer of 1912, when WittgensteinŌĆÖs sister visited Cambridge, Russell told her that he expected the next major advance in philosophy to come from her brother. The transformation was extraordinary. Wittgenstein had arrived without qualifications; he was now regarded as one of the most original minds in the field.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Cambridge proved decisive. It was perhaps the only institution that would have accepted him under such conditions. He was not required to sit examinations or submit essays. All that was required was RussellŌĆÖs assurance that he was worth listening to.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Logic as the Central Problem}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">What absorbed Wittgenstein during this period was not mathematics itself, but the nature of logical relations. We reason. We infer. We see that one proposition follows from another. But what makes this possible?</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">What are logical relations?</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein came to believe that logic is not a subject alongside others. It is not something that can be described from outside. Logic is already at work in language itself. Every meaningful proposition presupposes it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This insight led him to a decisive conclusion: that the attempt to construct a theory of logic was misguided.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Limits of Saying}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Russell and Frege had attempted to describe logicŌĆöto state its laws, to place it within a formal system. Wittgenstein began to suspect that this was the source of the contradiction.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Logic cannot be captured by propositions, because propositions already rely on it. To attempt to state the structure that makes stating possible is to presuppose what one is trying to explain.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Logical form does not belong to what can be said. It belongs to what shows itself whenever anything meaningful is said at all.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This distinctionŌĆöbetween what can be said and what can only be shownŌĆöfirst emerged for Wittgenstein in the context of logic. Only later would it extend to ethics, value, and meaning.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Parable: The Shadow}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Trying to give a theory of logic, Wittgenstein came to believe, is like trying to jump on oneŌĆÖs own shadow. No matter how one moves, the shadow moves with it. One cannot step outside what makes movement possible.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Logic, like the shadow, is not something we encounter as an object. It is present in every step we take.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Norway and Isolation}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">In 1913, Wittgenstein left Cambridge and moved to Norway, where he lived alone in a remote hut. He sought isolation deliberately. He believed that conversation, even with intelligent people, distracted him from clarity. Later, he would say that this year was the period when his mind was most alive.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">During this time, he worked obsessively on the problems Russell had, in effect, passed on to him. He became convinced that RussellŌĆÖs paradox was not a failure of technical ingenuity, but a failure to recognize the limits of language.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">There are things that cannot be said without contradiction. Logic is one of them.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Dictation and Discipline}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Although isolated, Wittgenstein did not entirely withdraw from communication. He dictated remarks to G.\ E.\ Moore, who made the difficult journey to visit him. Moore acted, in effect, as a recorder rather than a collaborator. Wittgenstein spoke; Moore wrote.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">These dictated remarks reveal how much of WittgensteinŌĆÖs early philosophy had already taken shape before the war. The analysis of propositions, logical form, and the structure of language was largely complete.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">What remained was to find a way of writing it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">In the summer of 1914, Wittgenstein returned briefly to Austria. Shortly afterward, the First World War began.
\section*{Mirrors and Frames}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A temptation runs through much of philosophy: the temptation to treat language as a mirror. On this view, words reflect the world. Sentences stand before reality and show it back to us, faithfully or otherwise. If the reflection is accurate, the sentence is true. If it is distorted, the sentence is false.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This picture is powerful, and it is not entirely wrong. But it conceals something essential.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A mirror shows what stands before it, but it also presupposes something that is rarely noticed: the frame.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The frame does not reflect anything. It does not depict the world. Yet without it, the mirror does not function as a mirror at all. The frame determines where the mirror begins and ends. It fixes orientation. It makes reflection possible without itself appearing in the reflection.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein came to believe that logic is not a mirror, but a frame.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Logic Is Not What Is Reflected}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Russell and others had attempted to describe logic as if it were another object in the worldŌĆöas if it could be placed before us and examined like a structure or a system. This approach treated logic as something that could be stated, formalized, and surveyed from the outside.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein saw a problem here. Logic is not one more thing among things. It does not describe how the world is arranged. It determines what it makes sense to describe at all.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Logical relations do not appear in propositions the way objects appear. They are already present in the possibility of meaning. To attempt to describe them as if they were facts is to mistake the frame for part of the reflection.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Why Frames Cannot Be Seen as Mirrors}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A mirror can be reflected in another mirror. A frame cannot frame itself.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This asymmetry mattered to Wittgenstein. Any proposition that says something already presupposes logical form. The form is not what the proposition says; it is what allows the proposition to say anything at all.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">To attempt to state logical form is therefore to rely on what one is trying to state. The effort collapses into circularity or contradiction. This, Wittgenstein believed, was not an accident in RussellŌĆÖs system, but a sign that the task itself was misconceived.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Logic cannot be represented without already being in force.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Parable: The Window and the Wall}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Imagine standing in a room with a large window. Through the window, you see the world outside. Trees, streets, people passing. The glass may be clear or fogged, but either way, it is what allows seeing.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Now imagine trying to look at the window in the same way you look at the trees. The moment you focus on it as an object, the view disappears.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The glass is not invisible, but it is not seen in the same way as what it reveals.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein came to think that logic stands to language as the window stands to the view. It is not something we look at, but something we look through.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{From Mirrors to Orientation}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This realization marked a shift in WittgensteinŌĆÖs thinking. Philosophy should not aim to produce better mirrorsŌĆöclearer reflections of realityŌĆöbut to understand the frames within which reflection is possible.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Such frames do not explain the world. They orient us within it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Later, this insight would extend beyond logic to language more generally. Words do not merely reflect reality; they function within practices that set the conditions for sense. Meaning does not lie behind language as a hidden object. It lies in the way language is already in use.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The philosopherŌĆÖs task, then, is not to polish the mirror endlessly, but to notice the frame that has been silently doing its work all along.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\section*{War and the Expansion of the Unsayable}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">When the First World War began, Wittgenstein did not greet it with celebration. Unlike some intellectuals of the period, he did not see the war as a cleansing historical force or a moment of collective renewal. His response was somber and personal.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He believed that the war would test him. Not politically, but ethically. He did not enlist out of patriotism. He was convinced that the British would ultimately prevail, and this did not trouble him. What mattered to him was something else entirely: whether he would emerge from the war as a more serious person.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Seriousness, for Wittgenstein, was not a mood. It was a condition of life lived without evasion.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Enlistment and Misunderstanding}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein enlisted in the Austrian army as a private. For a long time, however, he was kept away from direct danger. The authorities, aware of his family background, repeatedly assigned him to positions behind the lines. Wittgenstein, meanwhile, kept requesting transfers closer to the fighting.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A persistent misunderstanding followed. His superiors believed he was asking for greater safety. He was asking for the opposite.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">For the first years of the war, he served in relatively secure posts, including on a supply vessel operating along a river. During this time, he continued to write philosophy, carrying forward the work he had begun in Norway.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Book of the Gospels}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">While stationed inland, Wittgenstein entered a small bookshop. It contained only one book: a copy of Leo TolstoyŌĆÖs \emph{Gospel in Brief}. He bought it and read it repeatedly. The book had a profound effect on him.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He was rarely seen without it. Among his fellow soldiers, he became known as the man with the gospels.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The influence of the book was not theoretical. It did not provide him with doctrines. It intensified his demand for integrity. His notebooks from this period contain reflections on God, self-scrutiny, and resolve, written alongside logical remarks.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Notably, he separated these modes of writing. When he wrote philosophy, he used ordinary script. When he wrote about God, himself, or his family, he used a simple cipher he had learned as a child. The distinction was deliberate. Some things were not meant to be read casually.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Front and Exposure}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">In 1916, Wittgenstein was finally transferred to the front, where death was a daily presence. He served with distinction and was repeatedly recognized for his bravery. Exposure was no longer abstract. It was immediate and constant.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Something changes in his manuscripts at this point.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Until then, his philosophical writing had focused almost exclusively on logic: propositions, inference, and structure. Now, without abandoning that work, he began to write directlyŌĆöwithout codeŌĆöabout God, ethics, aesthetics, and the meaning of life.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The distinction he had developed in logic between what can be said and what must be shown was now applied more broadly.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Expansion of the Distinction}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein writes that to believe in God is to understand the meaning of life. He writes that to see the facts of the world clearly is to see that they are not the end of the matter. He writes that the solution to the problem of life is not an answer, but the disappearance of the problem.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">These remarks are striking not only for their content, but for their form. They are not coded. They are written as philosophy.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">What had begun as a technical insight about logic had expanded. Logic, ethics, aesthetics, and meaning now stood together. All belonged to what language could not state without distortion.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Language could describe the world.
It could not confer value upon it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Completion Under Constraint}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">As the war continued, the book that would become the \emph{Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus} took its final shape. What had begun as a work of logical analysis became something unprecedented: a combination of formal rigor and ethical restraint.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">It is unlikely that such a work could have been written without the conditions under which it was composed.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Near the end of the war, Wittgenstein was taken prisoner. It was during captivity that he completed the manuscript. The book ends not with a theory, but with silence.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Vulnerability}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The war also made vulnerability unavoidable. Wittgenstein witnessed injury, loss, and permanent change among those closest to him. The human body, once damaged, did not restore itself according to ideals.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Music, too, was altered but not extinguished.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">These experiences did not soften him. They sharpened his sense that life cannot be secured by explanation.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Parable: The Boundary}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Imagine walking to the edge of a map. The terrain does not end, but the map does. Continuing requires movement without representation.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein came to believe that philosophy must know where its map ends. Beyond that boundary, one does not theorize. One lives.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\section*{Courage, Discipline, and Seriousness}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein did not understand courage as confidence or bravado. He distrusted displays of fearlessness and regarded enthusiasm with suspicion. Courage, for him, was not a matter of temperament, but of endurance.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">To endure meant to remain present without consolation. It meant not turning away from difficulty, not disguising uncertainty as conviction, and not replacing action with speech. Courage was inseparable from restraint.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This understanding shaped his conduct long before the war, but the war made it unavoidable.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Discipline Without Doctrine}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Discipline, in WittgensteinŌĆÖs life, was not imposed by external rules. It was not adherence to a code. It was a self-imposed refusal to live loosely with respect to what mattered.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He demanded discipline in thinking, in work, and in personal conduct. Sloppiness was not merely an intellectual failure; it was a failure of attention. To think carelessly was to treat meaning lightly.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This is why he revised endlessly, destroyed drafts, and doubted publication. Writing was not a vehicle for expression, but a test of honesty. If something could not be said clearly, it should not be said at all.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Seriousness as Orientation}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Seriousness, for Wittgenstein, was not severity. It was orientation toward what is at stake.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A serious life is not one without joy or beauty. It is one in which joy and beauty are not used as distractions. Seriousness meant that nothing important was treated as a pastime.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Philosophy, ethics, music, and personal conduct all belonged to this same register. None were safe from scrutiny. None were permitted to become ornamental.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">To live seriously was to live without pretending that the most important things were easier than they are.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Courage and the Refusal of Consolation}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein was wary of consolation, especially when it came too quickly. Explanations can console. Theories can console. Even beliefs can console.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">But consolation, when it precedes clarity, dulls attention. It offers relief at the cost of understanding.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Courage, as he understood it, involved refusing this relief. It meant standing with difficulty long enough for it to show itself clearly, even if no answer followed.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Inner Measure}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He believed that there is a kind of measure internal to a life. One knows when one has acted honestly, and one knows when one has evaded something essential. No external recognition can substitute for this.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This belief underlies his rejection of hypocrisy. Saying the right words, holding the correct views, or occupying respected positions did not count for much if they were not matched by conduct.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Ethics was not a matter of justification. It was a matter of alignment.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Parable: The Straight Edge}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Imagine drawing a line freehand. It may look straight from a distance. Now place a straight edge beside it. The deviation becomes visible immediately.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The straight edge does not accuse the line. It simply reveals it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">For Wittgenstein, seriousness functioned in this way. It was not a moral judgment imposed from outside, but an internal standard against which oneŌĆÖs life was continually measured.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Preparation Without Assurance}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein did not believe that courage guaranteed clarity, or that discipline guaranteed understanding. There were no such assurances.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">What these qualities offered was not success, but preparedness. They prepared one to face uncertainty without distortion, and to stop speaking when speech no longer served truth.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This preparedness would shape the final form of the work he was completingŌĆöa book that would refuse to explain what explanation could not reach, and would end precisely where seriousness required it to end.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\section*{After the War, Before the Silence}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">When the war ended, Wittgenstein did not experience a return to normality. He believed that the culture he had grown up in had been irrevocably altered. The habits, assumptions, and forms of confidence that had once governed public life no longer seemed intact.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">For a time, he continued to wear his military uniform. This was not an expression of pride or nostalgia. It was a refusal to pretend that the break had not occurred. The uniform marked a boundary. What had come before, he believed, could not simply be resumed.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Persistence Without Restoration}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The war had not restored clarity; it had removed illusion.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He saw this most sharply in the lives around him. Injury did not always mean the end of form or discipline. One could lose a limb and continue to work, continue to practice, continue to shape meaning through effort rather than explanation.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Music did not vanish when the body was damaged. It changed its demands.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This mattered to Wittgenstein. It confirmed something he already suspected: that meaning does not depend on completeness, but on orientation. What survives is not what is explained, but what is practiced.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Book Takes Its Final Shape}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The work he had been writing through isolation, war, and captivity now reached its conclusion. What had begun as an inquiry into logic had expanded into a book that refused to separate clarity from restraint.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The final propositions of the book do not offer solutions. They remove temptation. They do not answer questions about value, meaning, or purpose. They show why such questions cannot be answered in the way philosophy had traditionally attempted.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The book ends not with knowledge, but with silence.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Captive to Pictures}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Looking back, Wittgenstein would later describe philosophical confusion as a form of captivity. We become held by picturesŌĆöways of imagining language, thought, or realityŌĆöthat feel inevitable. We struggle within them without realizing that the struggle itself is produced by the picture.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The task of philosophy, as he would later put it, is not to advance theory, but to show the way out. To show the fly the way out of the bottle.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This image was not yet present in the \emph{Tractatus}. But the impulse already was. The book does not replace one picture with another. It dismantles the frame that made the picture seem compulsory.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{From Solution to Dissolution}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">What Wittgenstein had come to seeŌĆöfirst in logic, then in ethics, and finally in lifeŌĆöwas that not all problems are solved by answers. Some are dissolved when the urge to answer them is relinquished.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This was not resignation. It was precision.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The seriousness he demanded of himself now took a new form. It was no longer enough to draw limits. One had to understand why the urge to cross them arose in the first place.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The silence at the end of the book was not the end of philosophy. It was the end of a certain way of doing it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\section*{Return Without Resolution}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">After completing the book, Wittgenstein believed that philosophy, as he had practiced it, was finished. The silence at the end of the \emph{Tractatus} was not rhetorical. It marked a genuine stopping point.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">For a time, he did not return to academic life. He worked, lived simply, and resisted the expectation that he should continue producing philosophy merely because he was able to. The book had done what it could do. To go further in the same way would have been dishonest.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Yet the problems did not disappear.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">They returned, not as questions demanding answers, but as tensions in how language was used and misunderstood. Wittgenstein began to notice that philosophical confusion did not arise only in technical contexts. It appeared in ordinary speech, in everyday reasoning, in the way people explained themselves and one another.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The silence had cleared something away, but it had not resolved everything.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{From Foundations to Therapy}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">When Wittgenstein eventually returned to philosophy, it was without the ambition to found anything. He no longer sought to describe the essence of language, logic, or thought. Instead, he turned his attention to how philosophical problems arise in the first place.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He came to see philosophy as a kind of therapy.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This did not mean consolation. It meant treatment. Philosophical problems, he believed, are not theoretical puzzles awaiting solutions. They are knots produced by misunderstandings about languageŌĆöby pictures that hold us captive.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">We imagine that all words must work in the same way. We imagine that meaning must be hidden behind use. We imagine that explanation must reach beneath practice to something more fundamental.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">These pictures generate anxiety. They compel us to ask questions that cannot be answered in the way they demand.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">PhilosophyŌĆÖs task, then, is not to answer these questions, but to show why they ariseŌĆöand how they can be let go.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Fly and the Bottle}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein later described philosophical confusion with a simple image: a fly trapped in a bottle. The fly beats itself against the glass, unable to escape, because it does not see the opening.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The task of philosophy is not to push the fly through the glass, nor to explain the physics of the bottle. It is to show the fly the way out.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This image reflects a profound shift. Philosophy no longer constructs frameworks. It loosens them. It does not replace one picture with another. It allows us to see that we were trapped by a picture at all.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Pictures and Compulsion}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">What makes philosophical pictures dangerous is not that they are false, but that they feel necessary. Once in place, they dictate what counts as an answer, what counts as understanding, and what counts as sense.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein came to believe that clarity consists in recognizing when a picture has outlived its usefulness.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This recognition cannot be forced. It comes through careful attention to ordinary language, to how words are actually used, and to where our explanations begin to run ahead of our practices.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The work of philosophy, in this later mode, is slow and untheatrical. It consists in returning words to the contexts in which they already function, and allowing confusion to dissolve.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\section*{Music, Injury, and Going On}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">WittgensteinŌĆÖs later thought is often described as a philosophy of practice. This emphasis did not arise in abstraction. It was shaped by lives lived under constraint.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He had seen how injury alters form without erasing it. The loss of a limb did not bring music to an end. It required reorientation. Technique changed. Discipline intensified. What mattered was not restoration, but continuation.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Music, in this sense, offered a model for meaning. One does not explain how to play. One practices. One learns how to go on.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Rule-Following and Continuation}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">In his later philosophy, Wittgenstein became absorbed by a deceptively simple question: what does it mean to follow a rule?</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Rules do not contain their own applications. No formulation dictates every future move. At some point, interpretation gives way to practice. One simply goes on.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This is not arbitrariness. It is training, participation, and shared form of life. To understand a rule is to be able to continue in a way that others recognize as correct.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Meaning, here, is not hidden behind action. It is displayed in it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Practice Without Explanation}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This emphasis on going on reflects WittgensteinŌĆÖs broader conviction that not everything meaningful rests on justification. Some forms of understanding show themselves only in what is done repeatedly and attentively.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Music again serves as a guide. One does not justify each note. One plays. One practices. One corrects oneself not by theory, but by listening.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The same, Wittgenstein believed, is true of language.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Uniform and Discontinuity}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">After the war, Wittgenstein sometimes continued to wear his uniform. This was not nostalgia, nor allegiance. It was an acknowledgment of rupture.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The war had ended one form of life. The continuity people expected did not exist. To dress as if nothing had changed would have been a kind of falsehood.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This sensitivity to rupture carried into his philosophy. He resisted the idea that intellectual life proceeds smoothly from one stage to another. Breaks matter. Discontinuities reshape what follows.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">One does not always repair what is broken. Sometimes one learns how to continue differently.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Seriousness Revisited}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">In his later years, seriousness no longer meant drawing sharp limits or ending with silence. It meant attending patiently to ordinary use, resisting the urge to explain too quickly, and stopping when words no longer clarified.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Philosophy, in this final form, did not aim at purity. It aimed at honesty.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The work ends not with a doctrine, but with an activity: looking carefully, untangling confusion, and then returning to life without the need for philosophical reinforcement.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">That, for Wittgenstein, was not a retreat from rigor.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">It was rigorŌĆÖs completion.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{War and the Seriousness of Speech}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">When the First World War began, Wittgenstein volunteered for service. He lived close to danger and monotony, where language was stripped of ornament. Commands, warnings, and reports mattered. Grand explanations did not.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">During this period, he kept notebooks in which logical remarks appeared alongside reflections on fear, duty, and resolve. War convinced him that ethical value does not describe how the world is, but how one stands within it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Ethics does not add facts to the world. It changes the way the world is faced.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">To speak of ethics as if it were a set of propositions, he believed, risks turning it into something cheap. Words about goodness can replace goodness itself. Language can become a shield rather than a guide.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">From this came one of his deepest convictions: that silence is not emptiness, but restraint.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{What Can Be Shown but Not Said}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The \emph{Tractatus} ends with a stark conclusion: that there are things which cannot be said, only shown. Logic can show itself in the structure of language. Ethics can show itself in how one lives. Beauty can show itself without explanation.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">To attempt to say these things directly is to distort them. Explanation becomes reduction. Reverence becomes repetition.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This led Wittgenstein to his most famous line:
\begin{quote}
What cannot be spoken of must be passed over in silence.
\end{quote}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This was not a dismissal of meaning, value, or depth. It was an attempt to protect them from misuse.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\section*{Renunciation and the Burden of Integrity}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">When the war ended, Wittgenstein returned to a world that no longer felt inhabitable in the same way. The intensity of exposure he had lived through had stripped many social forms of their credibility. Comfort, wealth, and polite distance now appeared less like achievements and more like obstructions.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He made a decision that would define the next phase of his life: he gave away his inheritance.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This was not a gesture of protest or generosity in the public sense. It was an act of alignment. Wittgenstein believed that wealth insulated a person from consequence and distorted oneŌĆÖs relation to reality. It allowed failure to be absorbed rather than felt. For someone concerned with clarity, this insulation was intolerable.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">To live honestly, he believed, required standing without buffers.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Austere Living}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein chose a life of deliberate simplicity. He worked as a village schoolteacher in rural Austria, far from intellectual circles. Later, he worked as a gardenerŌĆÖs assistant and in other forms of manual labor. These were not symbolic roles. He took them seriously, often too seriously.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He demanded discipline of himself and others. He could be harsh, especially when he believed carelessness was being mistaken for kindness. For Wittgenstein, to treat someone gently at the cost of truth was a form of disrespect.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">What troubled him most was hypocrisy: the gap between what one says and how one lives. Moral language, when detached from conduct, appeared to him as a kind of costumeŌĆösomething worn rather than inhabited.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Ethics, as he understood it, was first a duty to oneself. It was not about improving the world in the abstract, but about refusing to live in ways that required excuses.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Weight of the \emph{Tractatus}}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">During this period, Wittgenstein believed that his philosophical task had been completed. The \emph{Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus} had been published, and he thought it had solved the essential problems of philosophy by showing their limits.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The book presents itself as a structure of propositions, each resting on the previous ones. It aims to guide the reader toward a clear view of what can be meaningfully said. Once that view is reached, the structure is meant to disappear.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This intention is captured in one of the bookŌĆÖs most striking images.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Ladder}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein compares his own propositions to a ladder. One climbs it in order to reach a vantage point. But once there, the ladder must be thrown away. To cling to it would be to mistake the means for the end.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The propositions of the \emph{Tractatus} are not final truths about the world. They are tools for clarifying language. Once they have done their work, they are no longer needed.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This image reveals both the ambition and the fragility of the project. The book attempts to say precisely what can be said, in order to reveal what cannot.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">But this raised a troubling question, one that Wittgenstein could not ignore.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">If the book itself consists of sentences, and if many of its most important insights concern what cannot be said, then what exactly is the status of the book?</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{A Tension at the Core}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Over time, Wittgenstein began to sense that something in the \emph{Tractatus} was unstable. The book aimed to draw a sharp boundary between sense and nonsense. Yet the boundary itself seemed to be drawn from within language.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The propositions of the \emph{Tractatus} are not ordinary descriptions of facts. They do not picture possible situations in the world in the way everyday sentences do. Their role is different. They are meant to clarify the logical structure of language itself.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">But if meaning depends on use, and if these propositions are not used in ordinary ways, then their status becomes unclear.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein began to suspect that the very attempt to describe the essence of language might be misguided.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Parable: The Perfect Key}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Imagine a key designed to open all doors. It is crafted with extraordinary precision. But when tested, it fits no lock in particular. It is not that the key is poorly made. It is that locks are not all the same.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The problem is not technical, but conceptual.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein began to see that language might not have a single lock to which one master key could correspond.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Return of Doubt}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">These doubts did not come easily. Wittgenstein was not someone who abandoned ideas lightly. The \emph{Tractatus} had cost him years of concentration and strain. To question it was to question his own earlier certainty.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Gradually, however, he came to believe that the bookŌĆÖs vision of language was too rigid. It treated language as if its primary function were description, as if all meaningful sentences aimed to mirror facts.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">But in everyday life, language does much more than describe.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">We ask questions. We give orders. We tell jokes. We offer comfort. We express anger. We make promises. These uses do not fit neatly into the picture model.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The earlier framework, with its emphasis on logical form, seemed unable to account for this richness without forcing it into distortion.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{A Philosophical Pause}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">For a time, Wittgenstein withdrew almost entirely from philosophy. He lived, worked, and struggled with himself. He was uncertain whether philosophy, as he had practiced it, was even legitimate.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This withdrawal was not a rejection of seriousness, but an extension of it. If philosophy could not be practiced honestly, it should not be practiced at all.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He refused to continue merely because others expected him to. The question of whether philosophy was worth doing had to be answered by philosophy itself.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Silence, once again, was not absence. It was discipline.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\section*{The Turn Toward Ordinary Language}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Eventually, Wittgenstein returned to philosophy, though not with the sense of certainty that had marked his earlier work. He returned not to complete a system, but to investigate what had gone wrong in his previous way of thinking.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He resumed teaching at Cambridge, but his manner was unconventional. His lectures were exploratory rather than declarative. He paced, questioned, paused, and corrected himself. Philosophy, for him, was no longer a matter of constructing theories, but of attending carefully to how language is actually used.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This attention would reshape his understanding of meaning.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{From Structure to Use}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">In his later work, Wittgenstein abandoned the idea that language has a single underlying logical form. He began to see that his earlier focus on representation had narrowed his view.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Language, he now thought, is not primarily a mirror of the world. It is a set of human activities.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Words do not all serve the same purpose. Some describe facts, but others command, request, promise, warn, comfort, or amuse. Their meaning lies not in a hidden structure, but in their role within shared practices.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">To understand a word is not to grasp an abstract definition, but to know how to go on with it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Language Games}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein introduced the idea of \emph{language games} to emphasize this diversity. A language game is not merely speech, but speech embedded in action. Giving an order, following a recipe, telling a story, praying, joking, or teaching a child a word are all different language games.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Each has its own standards of correctness. What counts as understanding in one game may not count in another.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Problems arise when language is removed from its game and treated as if it must function everywhere in the same way. Philosophy often fails, Wittgenstein believed, by ignoring this variety.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Parable: The Misused Tool}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Imagine someone who owns only a hammer. Every problem begins to look like a nail. Delicate instruments are treated as obstacles rather than necessities.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein came to believe that philosophy had long suffered from this kind of fixation. It treated all language as if it were designed for description, and then wondered why so much of human speech refused to behave.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Meaning as Public Practice}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A crucial feature of WittgensteinŌĆÖs later view is that meaning is not private. Words gain their sense from shared use within a form of life. To follow a rule is not to consult an inner guide, but to participate in a practice that others can recognize.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This insight challenged the idea that meaning is something hidden inside the mind. Understanding is not a mental object. It is a capacity displayed in action.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">To say that someone understands a word is to say that they can use it appropriately within the relevant situations.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Family Resemblance}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">As Wittgenstein examined how words function in ordinary life, he noticed that many concepts resist strict definition. Rather than sharing a single essence, they are connected by overlapping similarities.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He described this pattern as \emph{family resemblance}. Members of a family may resemble one another in different waysŌĆöeye shape, voice, gestureŌĆöwithout any single feature common to all.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Concepts such as ŌĆ£game,ŌĆØ ŌĆ£art,ŌĆØ or ŌĆ£languageŌĆØ function in this way. Attempts to define them by necessary and sufficient conditions often fail, not because of ignorance, but because the concepts themselves are open-textured.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Understanding does not always require sharp boundaries.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Parable: The Rope}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A rope does not derive its strength from a single fiber running its entire length. Its strength lies in the overlapping of many fibers, each covering part of the span.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">So it is with many of our concepts. Their stability comes from interwoven uses, not from a hidden core.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Forms of Life}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Language games are not isolated. They belong to what Wittgenstein called \emph{forms of life}: the broader patterns of human activity within which language makes sense.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">To understand a word is to understand the life in which it is at home. Confusion arises when words are removed from their form of life and treated as if they carried meaning independently of context.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Philosophy, in this later view, is not a search for deep explanations, but an effort to restore words to their ordinary surroundings.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Philosophy as Therapy}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein described philosophy as a kind of therapy. It does not add knowledge in the way science does. Instead, it dissolves confusions by showing how language has gone astray.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Philosophical problems, he believed, often feel profound because language has trapped us in misleading pictures. The task is not to answer these problems, but to see them clearly enough that they lose their grip.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">When the confusion is gone, the urge to theorize often disappears with it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Style of the \emph{Philosophical Investigations}}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Unlike the \emph{Tractatus}, WittgensteinŌĆÖs later work does not present a linear argument. It consists of remarks, questions, examples, and counterexamples. The reader is invited to look, not to accept.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This form reflects the content. There is no final doctrine to absorb, only a method of attention.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Philosophy, as Wittgenstein now practiced it, aimed not at certainty, but at orientation.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\section*{Music, Conduct, and the Refusal of Paraphrase}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Throughout his life, music remained central to WittgensteinŌĆÖs understanding of meaning. It was not an interest alongside philosophy, but a standard against which philosophy was measured.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A musical phrase, he believed, does not describe something else. It does not stand in for an external fact. Its meaning is not captured by explanation, and any attempt to paraphrase it leaves something essential behind. One understands music by following it, not by translating it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This mattered deeply to Wittgenstein. Music showed that understanding need not involve representation, and that clarity need not involve explanation. Something can be precise without being reducible.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He came to believe that philosophy should aspire to this condition: exact, restrained, and incapable of being replaced by summary.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Showing Rather Than Saying}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Both in his early and later work, Wittgenstein maintained a distinction between what can be said and what can only be shown. What changed was his understanding of how showing works.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">In the \emph{Tractatus}, showing was tied to logical form. In his later philosophy, showing was tied to practice. Meaning shows itself in use, not in hidden structure.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Ethics, too, belongs here. To live well is not to possess a theory of goodness, but to act without self-deception. Ethical understanding is not demonstrated by speech, but by conduct.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">For Wittgenstein, the temptation to explain ethics was often a way of avoiding the difficulty of living it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Separate Social Worlds}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein lived in a time when the social lives of men and women were sharply divided. Expectations, roles, and forms of expression differed markedly. He was acutely aware that language grows within these social arrangements.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Words acquire their sense from the activities they accompany. When language formed in one social world is applied uncritically to another, misunderstanding follows. This is not a failure of intelligence, but a failure of attention.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Philosophical confusion often arises, he believed, from forgetting this dependence. We treat words as if they carried meaning on their own, independent of the lives that sustain them.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">To understand language is therefore to understand difference.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Observation Over Theory}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">WittgensteinŌĆÖs later philosophy emphasized observation rather than explanation. Instead of asking what a word really means, he asked how it is actually used. Instead of constructing models, he described practices.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This shift was not toward relativism or indifference. It was toward responsibility. To describe carefully is harder than to explain confidently. It requires patience and restraint.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Philosophy, he believed, should not compete with science or ideology. It should slow thought down, not accelerate it.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The Unease with Academia}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Although Wittgenstein taught at Cambridge and influenced generations of students, he remained uneasy with academic philosophy. He distrusted cleverness that detached itself from life. Philosophical brilliance, when pursued as an end in itself, struck him as a kind of evasion.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He worried that philosophy could become a profession devoted to producing puzzles rather than resolving them. When philosophical activity continues simply because it sustains itself, clarity is replaced by momentum.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">For Wittgenstein, philosophy was justified only so long as it removed confusion. Once it became ornamental, it lost its legitimacy.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Writing as Reluctance}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Wittgenstein wrote slowly and with hesitation. He revised relentlessly and doubted whether his remarks should be published at all. The fragmented form of his later work reflects this reluctance.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He did not want to offer doctrines that others could repeat. He wanted to change how people looked, not what they concluded.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The \emph{Philosophical Investigations} ends without resolution. There is no final position, no system to inherit. The reader is left not with answers, but with a way of proceeding.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{Parable: The Mirror}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Imagine a mirror placed before language. The mirror does not add anything. It does not improve what it reflects. It simply allows what is already there to be seen more clearly.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This was WittgensteinŌĆÖs ambition for philosophy. Not to advance thought, but to return it to itself.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\subsection*{The End of Explanation}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Near the end of his life, Wittgenstein no longer believed that philosophy could provide foundations. What it could offer was orientation: a way of freeing thought from pictures that held it captive.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">When confusion dissolves, explanation loses its urgency. What remains is life, carried on without theoretical reinforcement.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This, perhaps, is the quiet unity of his work. From the early insistence on the limits of language to the later attention to ordinary use, Wittgenstein sought a form of clarity that did not replace life, but left it intact.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">He did not offer a worldview. He offered a discipline of attention.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">And when that attention is sufficient, philosophy comes to rest.</p></div></div><section class="inline-media-container flex flex-col gap-1 clear-both"></section><section class="auth-notification flex flex-col gap-1"></section></div></div><div class="order-first sticky hidden @md/mainview:block top-11 h-0 opacity-0 group-focus-within:opacity-100 group-hover:opacity-100 -mr-[36px] @lg/mainview:-mr-12"><div class="min-h-7 py-4 flex flex-col gap-0.5"><button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 whitespace-nowrap text-sm font-medium leading-[normal] cursor-pointer focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-1 focus-visible:ring-ring disabled:opacity-60 disabled:cursor-not-allowed transition-colors duration-100 [&amp;_svg]:shrink-0 select-none text-fg-secondary hover:text-fg-primary hover:bg-button-ghost-hover disabled:hover:text-fg-secondary disabled:hover:bg-transparent [&amp;_svg]:hover:text-fg-primary h-10 w-10 rounded-full" type="button" aria-label="Edit" data-state="closed"><span style="opacity: 1; transform: none;"><svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="stroke-[2] size-4"><path d="M18.25 5.75C16.8693 4.36929 14.6307 4.36929 13.25 5.75L10.125 8.875L5.52404 13.476C4.86236 14.1376 4.45361 15.0104 4.36889 15.9423L4 20.0001L8.0578 19.6311C8.98967 19.5464 9.86234 19.1377 10.524 18.476L18.25 10.75C19.6307 9.36929 19.6307 7.13071 18.25 5.75V5.75Z" stroke="currentColor"></path><path d="M12.5 7.5L16.5 11.5" stroke="currentColor"></path></svg></span></button></div></div><div class="action-buttons h-8 mt-0.5 mb-2 flex flex-row flex-wrap w-full justify-end print:hidden"><div class="flex items-center w-max rounded-lg text-xs end-4 -mr-2 -mt-2 opacity-100 p-0 gap-0" style="bottom: 80px;"><button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 whitespace-nowrap text-sm font-medium leading-[normal] cursor-point